To create a simple search bar using PHP, we'll use HTML for the form structure and PHP to process the search query when submitted. This example will include a basic form with an input field for the user's search query and display the results in a `div` below.

**index.php**

```php
<?php
// Configuration - You can adjust this as needed
$databaseHost = 'localhost';
$databaseName = 'your_database_name';
$databaseUsername = 'your_username';
$databasePassword = 'your_password';

// Connect to database
$conn = new mysqli($databaseHost, $databasePassword);

// Check connection
if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}

// Function to search database and return results as a string
function searchDatabase($searchTerm) {
    global $conn;
    $query = mysqli_query($conn, "SELECT * FROM your_table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$searchTerm%'");
    if (mysqli_num_rows($query) > 0) {
        while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($query)) {
            echo '<p>' . $row['column_name'] . '</p>';
        }
    } else {
        echo '<p>No results found.</p>';
    }
}

// Check if form has been submitted
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    // Retrieve the search term from the form
    $searchTerm = $_POST["search"];

    // If search term is not empty, run the search query
    if ($searchTerm) {
        searchDatabase($searchTerm);
    }
}

?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Search Page</title>
</head>

<body>
    <form method="post" action="<?php echo $_SERVER["PHP_SELF"]; ?>">
        <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Enter your search term here...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php if (isset($_POST['search']) && $_POST['search'] != ''): ?>
        <div class="results">
            <!-- Search results will be displayed here -->
        </div>
    <?php endif; ?>

</body>

</html>
```

**Important Points:**

- Make sure to replace `'your_database_name'`, `'your_username'`, `'your_password'`, and `'your_table_name'` with your actual database information and table name.
- The `searchDatabase()` function searches for the term in a column named `column_name`. Adjust this according to your needs.
- This is a basic example. You might want to enhance it by handling errors more robustly, adding pagination, or optimizing queries for large datasets.

Remember, security best practices should always be followed when dealing with user input (like search terms) to prevent SQL injection attacks. In this example, the LIKE query uses `%$searchTerm%`, which is a common method but might not be the most efficient way to search databases. For more complex scenarios or larger datasets, consider using parameterized queries or prepared statements for better security and performance.

